04280nam a22006255i 9780814733318DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147333187 a10.18574/nyu/9780814733318.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547535  a(OCoLC)779828451  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUG633b.G46 2001 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a355.4/22qOCoLC221/eng/202302161 aGentile, Gian P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Effective is Strategic Bombing? :bLessons Learned From World War II to Kosovo /cGian P. Gentile. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Origins of the American Conceptual Approach to Strategic Bombing and the United States Strategic Bombing Survey -- t2. The United States Strategic Bombing Survey and the Future of the Air Force -- t3. The Evaluation of Strategic Bombing against Germany -- t4. The Survey Presents Its Findings from Europe and Develops an Alternate Strategic Bombing Plan for Japan -- t5. The Evaluation of Strategic Bombing against Japan -- t6. A-Bombs, Budgets, and the Dilemma of Defense -- t7. A Comparison of the United States Strategic Bombing Survey with the Gulf War Air Power Survey -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of World War II, Secretary of War Henry L. Stimson and President Harry S. Truman established the U.S. Strategic Bombing Survey, to determine exactly how effectively strategic air power had been applied in the European theater and in the Pacific. The final study, consisting of over 330 separate reports and annexes, was staggering in its size and emphatic in its conclusions. As such it has for decades been used as an objective primary source and a guiding text, a veritable Bible for historians of air power. In this aggressively revisionist volume, Gian Gentile examines afresh this influential document to reveal how it reflected to its very foundation the American conceptual approach to strategic bombing. In the process, he exposes the survey as largely tautological and thereby throwing into question many of the central tenets of American air power philosophy and strategy. With a detailed chapter on the Gulf War and the resulting Gulf War Air Power Survey, and a concluding chapter on the lessons of the Kosovo air war, How Effective is Strategic Bombing? is the most comprehensive and important book on air power strategy in decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBombing, AerialzUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAerial operations, American. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081473135240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814733318.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814733318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814733318/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles